{{Infobox museum | name = Blood Road Museum | native_name = Blodveimuseet | native_name_lang = no | logo = | logo_upright = | logo_alt = | logo_caption = | image = | image_upright = | alt = | caption = | map_type = Nordland#Norway | map_relief = | map_size = | map_caption = Location in [[Nordland]] | coordinates = {{Coord|67|6|5.72|N|15|25|38.71|E|display=inline,title}} | former_name = | established = <!-- {{Start date|YYYY|MM|DD|df=y}} --> | dissolved = <!-- {{End date|YYYY|MM|DD|df=y}} --> | location = [[Saltdal]], [[Norway]] | type = | accreditation = | key_holdings = | collections = | collection_size = | visitors = | founder = | director = | president = | ceo = | chairperson = | curator = | architect = | historian = | owner = | publictransit = | car_park = | parking = | network = | website = http://nordlandsmuseet.no/blodveimuseet/ | embedded = }}
The '''Blood Road Museum''' ({{lang-no|Blodveimuseet}}) is a museum in [[Saltdal]] in [[Nordland]] county, [[Norway]]. The museum is located about {{convert|2|km|sp=us}} north of the center of [[Rognan]] and stands in the yard of the Saltdal Museum,<ref>[http://nordlandsmuseet.no/blodveimuseet/ Blood Road Museum at Nordland Museum]</ref> which is part of the [[Nordland Museum]].{{cn|date=December 2016}}
[[File:2013 08 06 Jugoslav churchyard in Botn M.JPG|thumb|left|Yugoslav cemetery in Botn]] The museum documents the history of the Yugoslav, Polish, and Soviet prisoners of war that built the [[Blood Road]] between Rognan and [[Langset (Saltdal)|Langset]] in the [[List of municipalities of Norway|municipality]] of [[Saltdal]] between 1942 and 1945 under the direction of the [[Reichskommissariat Norwegen|German occupation authorities]].<ref>Bohn, Robert, Christoph Cornelissen, & Karl Christian Lammers (eds.). 2008. ''Vergangenheitspolitik und Erinnerungskulturen im Schatten des Zweiten Weltkriegs: Deutschland und Skandinavien seit 1945''. Essen: Klartext Verlag, p. 192</ref> It also tells about how the prisoners of war lived and worked in the [[Dunderland Valley]], [[Nord-Rana]], and [[Korgen]].{{cn|date=December 2016}}
There are two cemeteries in [[Botn, Saltdal|Botn]], one for the Yugoslavs and another for the Germans. There is also a Soviet memorial where there was formerly a Soviet cemetery.{{cn|date=December 2016}} {{clear left}} ==References== {{reflist}}
==External links== * [http://nordlandsmuseet.no/blodveimuseet/ Blood Road Museum at Nordland Museum]
