{{italic title}}
The '''''Galician–Volhynian Chronicle''''' (ukr. ''Галицько-Волинський літопис'') is a historical record covering 1201–1292<ref name=mag>{{cite book|title=Galicia: A Historical Survey and Bibliographic Guide|first=Paul R. |last=Magocsi |year=1983 |publisher=University of Toronto Press|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=qgTrJm85sDQC&pg=PA53 |page=53 |isbn=0-8020-2482-3}}</ref> in the history of the Principality of [[Galicia-Volhynia]] (in modern [[Ukraine]]). The original chronicle did not survive; the oldest known copy is in the ''[[Hypatian Codex]]''.<ref name=mag/> The compiler of the ''Galician–Volhynian Chronicle'' explained Galicia's claim to the [[Principality of Kiev]].<ref>{{cite book| title=Ukraine and Russia in Their Historical Encounter: In Their Historical Encounter |first=Peter J. |last=Potichnyj  |author2=Marc Raeff |author3=Jaroslaw Pelenski |author4=Gleb N. Zekulin  |publisher= CIUS Press |year=1992 |isbn=0-920862-84-5 |page=9 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=iuFB8V2X4yEC&pg=PA9}}</ref> The first part of the chronicle (Daniel of Galicia chronicle) was written in [[Chełm|Kholm]] and possibly by a boyar Dionisiy Pavlovich.<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20150718231711/http://litopys.org.ua/istkult2/ikult217.htm Literature of the late Middle Ages]. Izbornik.</ref>

The chronicle was published in English translation with index and annotations by George A. Perfecky.<ref>{{cite book| first=George A. |last=Perfecky |title=The Galician-Volynian Chronicle |location=Munich |publisher=Wilhelm Fink Verlag |year=1973 |oclc=902306}}</ref> [[Daniel Waugh (historian)|Daniel Clarke Waugh]] published a review of this edition, which points out some flaws in translation.<ref>{{cite journal| first=Daniel Clarke |last=Waugh | author-link = Daniel Waugh (historian) |journal=[[Slavic Review]] |title=Review |volume=33 |issue=4 |date=Dec 1974 |pages=769–771  | jstor=2494516}}</ref>

